Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @sweet potatoes{2} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a large
drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tender and
slightly crispy, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim and mince @scallions{2}(trimmed and minced), separating whites from greens.
Peel @ginger{1%thumb} and grate using a #zester{} or the small holes of a #box grater{}
until you have ¾ tsp (1 1/2 tsp for 4 servings). Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, scallion greens, ¾ tsp
@soy sauce{2%tablespoon}, ¼ tsp grated ginger, ¼ tsp @sugar{1/4%teaspoon}, and a pinch
of garlic (use 1 1/2 tsp soy sauce, ½ tsp ginger, and ½ tsp sugar for 4 servings).

In a #large bowl{}, gently combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, scallion whites, half the
remaining soy sauce (all for 4 servings), remaining grated ginger, and remaining garlic.

Form into two patties (four patties for 4), each slightly wider than a burger bun.

When sweet potatoes have ~{10%minutes} left, heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{}
over medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per
side.

While burgers cook, halve and toast @potato buns{2} in #toaster{}.

Spread cut sides of buns with aioli (save some for dipping), then fill with patties,
@sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, and @crispy fried onions{1}.

Divide burgers and sweet potato wedges between plates. Serve with remaining aioli on
the side for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.